                "description": "<p>Konnichiwa! (Hello)</p><p>Are you ready to dive into the fascinating world of the Japanese writing system? Fasten your seatbelts and get ready for an exhilarating journey as we take off into an exploration like no other!</p><h2><strong>The Japanese Writing System</strong></h2><p>Imagine the Japanese writing system as a delicious four-season pizza, where each slice represents a distinct writing system. Just like the four seasons come together to create a harmonious whole, these writing systems combine to form the Japanese writing system. Now, let's savor each 'slice' of the Japanese writing pizza and explore its rich flavors.</p><figure class='image'><img src='https://skerlingo.com/assets/ckeditor/Pizza1_1685316017.png'></figure><p>&nbsp;</p><p>1. Kanji: Characters based on the Chinese script. They might seem complicated, like&nbsp;日本語 (Nihongo: Japanese). We won't dive into Kanji for now; beginners can start by learning hiragana, katakana, and then kanji.</p><p>Examples:&nbsp;</p><p>1.車 (kuruma&nbsp;: car)</p><figure class='image'><img src='https://skerlingo.com/assets/ckeditor/image_1685316038.png'></figure><p>2.学生&nbsp;(gakusei&nbsp;: student)</p><figure class='image'><img src='https://skerlingo.com/assets/ckeditor/image_1685316049.png'></figure><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Kana:</strong></p><p>Think of the Kana as half of the pizza. The term 'Kana' includes both Hiragana and Katakana, the two writing systems that we'll explore together.</p><p>2. Hiragana: Used to transcribe Japanese sounds, typically utilized with words of Japanese or Chinese origin.</p><p>Examples:&nbsp;</p><ol><li>すし&nbsp;(sushi: sushi)&nbsp;</li></ol><figure class='image'><img src='https://skerlingo.com/assets/ckeditor/image_1685316062.png'></figure><ol><li>ふぐ(fugu: blowfish)</li></ol><figure class='image'><img src='https://skerlingo.com/assets/ckeditor/image_1685316073.png'></figure><p>There are 46 basic hiragana sounds organized into a very intuitive and convenient chart where columns represent the 5 vowels of Japanese, and the rows indicate the consonants.</p><figure class='image'><img src='https://skerlingo.com/assets/ckeditor/image_1685316084.png'></figure><p>Except for the 5 vowels, each cell of the chart represents a consonant-vowel combination character or one of the 5 Japanese vowels. Together, these cells represent the complete set of basic Hiragana characters.&nbsp;</p><p>You can access the Hiragana chart from the app's lesson menu by clicking on the icon located in the top-right corner.</p><figure class='image'><img src='https://skerlingo.com/assets/ckeditor/image_1685316106.png'></figure><p>2. Katakana: This system also represents Japanese sounds. However, Katakana is mainly used to transcribe foreign words, brand names, product logos, anime titles or characters, animal and plant names, scientific and technical terms, etc. You can also access the Katakana chart from the Katakana lesson menu using the same icon as for Hiragana.</p><p>Katakana Examples:&nbsp;</p><p>1. ナルト: Naruto (Naruto; the anime)</p><figure class='image'><img src='https://skerlingo.com/assets/ckeditor/image_1685316127.png'></figure><p>2.パン: (pan&nbsp;: bread)</p><figure class='image'><img src='https://skerlingo.com/assets/ckeditor/image_1685316140.png'></figure><p>&nbsp;4. Romaji: The standard alphabet used when beginners want to learn Japanese Hiragana or Katakana. It is also used in some abbreviations like JR, which stands for Japanese Railways Group.</p><p>You might be still wondering how a Japanese sentence is written. It combines all four systems together. And here is one example:</p><figure class='image'><img src='https://skerlingo.com/assets/ckeditor/Japanese Sentence_1685316262.png'></figure><p>This sentence means: 'I ate pizza with my friends.' And as you can see, there are a lot of ingredients for one sentence, but don't worry, you'll feel more comfortable after you learn Hiragana and Katakana!</p><p>1, 2, 3, Let's GO!</p>",
