                "introduction": "Modified Hiragana",
                "description": "<h2><strong>Diacritic Marks in Japanese - Dakuten &amp; Handakuten</strong></h2><p>In the Japanese writing system, diacritic marks play a crucial role in modifying the sounds of hiragana and katakana characters. Two important diacritic marks are dakuten (ten-ten or tenten) and handakuten (maru or circle).</p><h3><strong>Dakuten:</strong></h3><p>Dakuten are two small strokes added to the upper-right corner of hiragana or katakana characters. They indicate a voiced sound in the syllable.</p><p>Examples:</p><ul><li>か&nbsp;(ka) becomes&nbsp;が(ga)</li><li>は&nbsp;(ha) becomes&nbsp;ば(ba)</li><li>た&nbsp;(ta) becomes&nbsp;だ(da)</li></ul><p>Note: When using dakuten, the 'g' sound should be pronounced like the 'g' in 'garden' and not as a 'j' sound.</p><h3><strong>Handakuten:</strong></h3><p>Handakuten is a small circle added to the upper-right corner of the 'h' line in hiragana and katakana. It transforms the 'h' sound into a 'p' sound.</p><p>Examples:</p><ul><li>は&nbsp;(ha) becomes&nbsp;ぱ(pa)</li><li>ひ&nbsp;(hi) becomes&nbsp;ぴ(pi)</li><li>ふ&nbsp;(fu) becomes&nbsp;ぷ(pu)</li></ul><p>Note: The 'f' sound in 'fu' is pronounced more like a 'hu' sound, not a true 'f' sound.</p><h3><strong>Conclusion</strong></h3><p>By adding dakuten or handakuten to hiragana or katakana characters, we can create new syllables with different phonetic values. This expands the range of sounds that can be represented in the Japanese language. Understanding these diacritic marks is essential for accurately pronouncing and reading Japanese words and sentences.</p><p>Please refer to the following table for an overview of the usage of dakuten and handakuten. Enjoy!</p><p>&nbsp;</p><figure class='image'><img src='https://skerlingo.com/assets/ckeditor/Lesson 12_1685635955.png'></figure>",
                "text_en": "Lesson 11",
                "label_en": "Lesson 11",
                "introduction_en": "Modified Hiragana",
                "description_en": "<h2><strong>Diacritic Marks in Japanese - Dakuten &amp; Handakuten</strong></h2><p>In the Japanese writing system, diacritic marks play a crucial role in modifying the sounds of hiragana and katakana characters. Two important diacritic marks are dakuten (ten-ten or tenten) and handakuten (maru or circle).</p><h3><strong>Dakuten:</strong></h3><p>Dakuten are two small strokes added to the upper-right corner of hiragana or katakana characters. They indicate a voiced sound in the syllable.</p><p>Examples:</p><ul><li>か&nbsp;(ka) becomes&nbsp;が(ga)</li><li>は&nbsp;(ha) becomes&nbsp;ば(ba)</li><li>た&nbsp;(ta) becomes&nbsp;だ(da)</li></ul><p>Note: When using dakuten, the 'g' sound should be pronounced like the 'g' in 'garden' and not as a 'j' sound.</p><h3><strong>Handakuten:</strong></h3><p>Handakuten is a small circle added to the upper-right corner of the 'h' line in hiragana and katakana. It transforms the 'h' sound into a 'p' sound.</p><p>Examples:</p><ul><li>は&nbsp;(ha) becomes&nbsp;ぱ(pa)</li><li>ひ&nbsp;(hi) becomes&nbsp;ぴ(pi)</li><li>ふ&nbsp;(fu) becomes&nbsp;ぷ(pu)</li></ul><p>Note: The 'f' sound in 'fu' is pronounced more like a 'hu' sound, not a true 'f' sound.</p><h3><strong>Conclusion</strong></h3><p>By adding dakuten or handakuten to hiragana or katakana characters, we can create new syllables with different phonetic values. This expands the range of sounds that can be represented in the Japanese language. Understanding these diacritic marks is essential for accurately pronouncing and reading Japanese words and sentences.</p><p>Please refer to the following table for an overview of the usage of dakuten and handakuten. Enjoy!</p><p>&nbsp;</p><figure class='image'><img src='https://skerlingo.com/assets/ckeditor/Lesson 12_1685635955.png'></figure>",
