                "introduction": "Mini Ya, Yu, Yo",
                "description": "<h2>Mini Ya, Yu, Yo: Creating New Sound Combinations</h2><p>The mini ya, yu, yo modification allows us to create additional sound combinations in the Japanese writing system. While its actual name differs, for the sake of simplicity, we will refer to it as mini ya, yu, yo.</p><p>By writing ya, yu, and yo in a smaller font size (や→ゃ,&nbsp;ゆ→ゅ,&nbsp;よ→ょ), we can explore new phonetic possibilities. These small characters (ゃ,&nbsp;ゅ, and&nbsp;ょ) are added after a hiragana with the vowel 'i' such as&nbsp;き (ki),&nbsp;ぎ (gi),&nbsp;し (shi),&nbsp;ち (chi), and so on.&nbsp;</p><p>In these cases, the 'i' sound is not pronounced. For instance,&nbsp;きゃ is pronounced as 'kya' and not 'kiya'. This subtle distinction can significantly alter the meaning of a word. Let's consider the following example:</p><p>びよういん (biyouin): beauty salon</p><p>びょういん (byouin): hospital</p><p>As you can see, the addition of mini yo (ょ) transforms the pronunciation and distinguishes between 'beauty salon' and 'hospital'.</p><p>Note: The 'u' sound can also be added to these syllables to extend the sound of 'yo' or 'yu'. For example,&nbsp;とうきょう (toukyou) is actually pronounced as 'tookyoo'. Similarly,&nbsp;きゅう (nine) is pronounced as 'kyuu'. These rules apply to both hiragana and katakana characters.</p><p>Please refer to the reference table below for further examples and clarification.</p><h2><strong>Hiragana:</strong></h2><figure class='image'><img src='https://skerlingo.com/assets/ckeditor/Lesson12 hiragana_1685639399.png'></figure><h2><strong>Katakana:</strong></h2><figure class='image'><img src='https://skerlingo.com/assets/ckeditor/Lesson12 katakana_1685643628.png'></figure>",
