                "label_fr": "Leçon12",
                "introduction_fr": "Les mini ya, yu, yo",
                "description_fr": "<h2>Mini&nbsp; ya, yu, yo</h2><p>The actual name is not mini ya, yu, yo but for the sake of ease we will use it. Thanks to this slight modification where&nbsp;ya, yu and yo are written in a smaller size&nbsp;や→ゃ、ゆ→ゅ、よ→ょwe will be able to create other sound combination. Those small &nbsp;ゃ、ゅ andょ&nbsp;comes actually after a hiragana with the vowel “i” like&nbsp;き(ki)、ぎ(gi)、し(shi)、ち(chi) etc. The following table will make it clearer.</p><p>In these cases, the sound “i” is not pronounced, for example&nbsp;きゃ is pronounced kya and not kiya.&nbsp;</p><p>This small difference can change the meaning of a word, for example:</p><p>びよういん(biyouin)&nbsp;: beauty salon&nbsp;</p><p>びょういん (byouin)&nbsp;: hospital</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>P.S&nbsp;: «&nbsp;u&nbsp;» can be added to these syllables to extend the sound of «&nbsp;yo&nbsp;» or «&nbsp;yu&nbsp;».&nbsp;</p><p>For example&nbsp;とうきょう(toukyou) is actually pronounced tookyoo. And&nbsp;きゅう(nine) is pronounced kyuu.&nbsp;</p><p>The same rules are applied to the katakana as you can see in there reference table below.</p><p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p><p><strong>hiragana</strong></p><figure class='image'><img src='https://skerlingo.dromen.agency/assets/ckeditor/mini ya yu yo 1_1671128180.png'></figure><p><strong>katakana</strong></p><p>&nbsp;</p><figure class='image'><img src='https://skerlingo.dromen.agency/assets/ckeditor/mini ya yu yo -katakana_1671128195.png'></figure>",
