                "introduction": "Pronunciation Rules Summary",
                "description": "<h2>Japanese sounds pronounciation summary:</h2><ol><li>い (i) is pronounced like the 'ee' in 'eel.'</li><li>In certain words like 'but' (shikashi), the&nbsp;い (i) sound may not be pronounced, resulting in 'shkashi' pronunciation.</li><li>え (e) is always pronounced like the 'e' in 'elephant.'</li><li>In some cases, the &nbsp;う (u) sound is not pronounced. For example, in the word for being tired, 'tsukareru,' it is often pronounced as 'tskareru.' Similarly, the auxiliary verb 'desu' is often pronounced as 'dess.'</li><li>し (shi) replaces the sound for 'si.'</li><li>ち (chi) replaces the sound for 'ti' and is pronounced like the “chea” in 'cheat.'</li><li>つ (tsu) replaces 'tu.'</li><li>The 'h' sound in Japanese is well-aspirated.</li><li>は (ha) is pronounced as 'wa' when used as a topic particle.</li><li>ヘ (he) is pronounced as 'e' when used as a place indicator particle.</li><li>ふ (fu) replaces 'hu' and is pronounced with a slight aspiration, as if blowing off a candle.</li><li>The 'r' sound in Japanese can be pronounced as an “r” and also as an “l”</li><li>The 's' sound in Japanese is never pronounced as a 'z' unless the modified kana (tenten) is used. Otherwise, it's always pronounced as the 's' in 'sun.'</li><li>を (wo) is often pronounced as 'o' in modern Japanese, despite being written as 'wo.'</li><li>In modern Japanese, the sounds of&nbsp;じ (ji) and&nbsp;ぢ (di), as well as&nbsp;ず (zu) and&nbsp;づ (du), are often pronounced the same way, usually as 'ji' and 'zu' respectively. However, some subtle distinctions may still exist depending on the dialect or speaker.</li><li>を (wo) is often pronounced as 'o' in modern Japanese, despite being written as 'wo.'</li><li>ん (n) at the end of a word or before certain consonants is pronounced with a nasal sound, like the 'n' in 'song.'</li><li>っ (small tsu) indicates a double consonant sound where the following consonant is pronounced with a pause or stop before it.</li><li>ー (long vowel mark) elongates the preceding vowel sound for katakana.</li></ol>",
